<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Whittle Hires Turner Aide
   As Chairman of New Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS TBSA TWX
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Whittle Communications L.P. hired the top
sales executive of Turner Broadcasting System Inc. to serve
as chairman of a new unit that includes the classroom news
service Channel One.
   Knoxville, Tenn.-based Whittle said Farrell Reynolds will
serve as chairman and chief executive officer of Whittle
Educational Network. Mr. Reynolds, a 10-year veteran of
Turner Broadcasting, had overseen all ad sales for Turner
cable networks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new unit includes all of Whittle's properties, such as
magazines, advertiser-supported wall posters and television
programs, aimed at U.S. schools.
   The unit's largest property is Channel One, the daily TV
news show for high school students; the show, which includes
commercials, began airing in March.
   Educators have called Channel One blatant
commercialization of public education. So far, 3,600 schools
in 38 states have signed contracts to air the 12-minute daily
program. Turner competes against Channel One with "CNN
Newsroom," a free 15-minute daily news program without ads.
   Christopher Whittle, chairman of Whittle Communications,
50%-owned by Time Warner Inc., said that the new unit plans
to create more TV channels in the next three years and that
some services may be expanded overseas.
</TEXT>
