<HL>
   Czechs Seek to Rebuild Tourism Industry
   ---
   Western Investment Is
   Seen as Part of Solution
   ----
   By Susan Carey
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4E
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   KARLOVY VARY, Czechoslovakia -- As director of the Hotel
Imperial, an imposing sanitarium in this western Bohemia spa
town, Stanislav Siroky is in what appears to be an ideal
situation.
   "We're booked to the last bed year round," says the
earnest physician, a 20-year veteran of the Imperial.
"Absolutely no marketing has ever been necessary."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Karlovy Vary, called Carlsbad in German, is an elegant
"fin de siecle" resort built along the River Tepla. Its
natural hot springs are said to soothe numerous health
disorders. Located 75 miles from Bayreuth, West Germany,
Karlovy Vary has an airport and a golf course, and is filled
with fanciful architecture. The Imperial sits high above the
town, offering a sweeping view of the soft green hills of
Slovkov Forest.
   But there are a few hitches. "Our prices are loss-making,"
says Dr. Siroky, so the building itself is falling apart.
"Nobody on the staff is very interested in working here," he
adds, so service standards are low and turnover high.
Finally, "the guests are impoverished," he notes. "We want to
change our clientele."
   Dr. Siroky's plight could describe the tourism industry in
all of Czechoslovakia -- and, indeed, throughout the East
Bloc. Tourists are rushing in, but mostly from Socialist
countries whose currencies are nearly worthless. Hotel and
spa managers don't know how to sell their attractions, much
less how to lure lucrative but demanding Western guests.
Employees are surly and discontented.
   For the past 50 years, there has been little investment in
infrastructure, so hotel rooms are in short supply, hotels
themselves are in disrepair, and restaurants, shopping and
amusements are lacking.
   The tourism potential is difficult to gauge. It remains to
be seen whether the countries of the region will be able to
accommodate, feed and entertain masses of Western travelers
in reasonable style.
   In the wake of Czechoslovakia's November revolution, the
new government has passed several laws in the hope of
creating an investment climate in which Western money and
know-how can turn the country's tourism industry into a
hard-currency machine. But the transformation will be
difficult, and the road ahead for Czechoslovak tourism
entrepreneurs and Western investors promises to be bumpy.
   The Hotel Imperial, a 78-year-old property, originally
part of an Anglo-French luxury hotel chain, has since 1945
been reserved exclusively for clients from the Soviet Union.
Moscow owned the hotel from the end of World War II until
1957, when it transferred the 420-bed property to the
Czechoslovak state -- with the proviso that only Soviets
could be treated here, and at fixed rates. The average price
paid by Soviet guests is so low -- 140 Czechoslovak crowns a
day ($4 at the official tourist rate) for room, full board
and treatments -- that Prague has had to spend the equivalent
of $600,000 to $700,000 a year subsidizing the Imperial's
operation.
   Thus, the once grand hotel has fallen into disrepair.
Balconies are closed to guests owing to falling plaster from
the facade. A recent windstorm ripped tiles from the roof,
and water leaks into the attic. Furnishings are early-1960s
style, and a third of the rooms lack a private bath.
   A volunteer team of Karlovy Vary architects and engineers,
working in secret on a renovation plan, estimates it would
cost about $7 million to bring the Imperial up to a minimum
Western standard.
   Down the hill in town, the Grand Hotel Pupp faces some of
the same problems. A hotel has stood on this riverfront site
since 1701, and the current building, an ornate white
confection, dates from 1893.
   The Pupp (which dropped the name, Grand Hotel Moskva, in
January) has entertained a who's who of guests during the
centuries. Beethoven and Paganini conducted in the hotel's
baroque performance hall. King Juan Carlos of Spain held a
family party in the French restaurant. Hollywood luminaries
lodge here during the Karlovy Vary film festival.
   But on a recent day, the place looks run-down, and the
staff doesn't appear to believe in service with a smile. The
380-room hotel is fully booked, but for those lucky enough to
have secured a room there is no hot water or heating today.
   Western companies are sniffing around Karlovy Vary and
elsewhere in Czechoslovakia for investment opportunities. Dr.
   Siroky says a West German company offered to buy the
Imperial for 500 million marks ($295 million). Josef Remes,
the food and beverage manager at the Pupp, says he has had
"quite a few offers" of assistance from Western hotel
companies and investment firms.
   In the municipal office, Jiri Kovarik, the mayor of
Karlovy Vary, welcomes the avalanche of Western interest.
According to the mayor, Swedish, French and Japanese concerns
have written or visited with plans to redevelop the city's
spa complex. One West German company wants to start a
building-repair firm, while another has offered to help
reorganize the Hotel Imperial. Mr. Kovarik says an Israeli
tour operator has promised to send a planeload of spa clients
to Karlovy Vary every day"but we are not yet well equipped
for this," he concedes.
   Ivan Chadima, who currently manages New York's upscale
United Nations Plaza Hotel, and several partners (some of
whom are Czechoslovak-Americans) have started a company
called EuroInvest to negotiate with Western partners on
behalf of the Czechoslovak tourism industry and to search for
Western partners for specific projects. EuroInvest hopes to
land a contract with Karlovy Vary.
   Mr. Chadima, who trained at the hotel school in the spa
Marianske Lazne (Marienbad in German) and worked in Prague
before fleeing to North America in 1968, is leaving his New
York job next month to work full-time for EuroInvest.
   "It will be six to 12 months before deals will be
possible," he says. "But these first deals will be closely
watched," he adds, so they have to be well structured and
beneficial to both parties. Otherwise, investor interest will
sour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0123.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Utahans Leave Restraint at Home,
   Stream North for Forbidden Fruit
   ----
   By Con Psarras
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKLIN, Idaho -- For thousands of hopeful Utahans, La
Tienda is a merchant of dreams.
   Actually, it's a convenience store, and just about the
only retail establishment in this pastoral town of 400 just
north of the Utah border. But besides selling Hostess
Twinkies and pumping gasoline, La Tienda (Spanish for "the
shop") also happens to be the only vendor of Idaho lottery
tickets that's within an easy drive of its more conservative
neighbor to the south.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last year, when Idaho approved a lottery, it projected
annual revenue of about $25 million. But it hadn't figured on
a gold rush of gambling-starved patrons from Utah, which
doesn't have a lottery. First-year lottery sales have
rocketed to $53 million, an increase fueled largely by the
Utah buying frenzy.
   While the lottery has been a boon to Idaho coffers, some
Utahans have complained that their state is losing valuable
revenue it could easily capture by adopting a lottery of its
own. But past efforts to create a Utah lottery have failed
miserably in the state Legislature, dominated as it is by
members of the conservative Mormon Church, which frowns on
gambling.
   That leaves La Tienda ideally situated. While Idaho
licenses hundreds of lottery-ticket vendors, the store has
emerged as the state's highest-volume dealer, recently
surpassing $1 million in total sales to date of the $1
tickets. Each day, a steady stream of cars clogs the two-lane
highway that connects Franklin with the more populous Utah
town of Logan, about 21 miles away.
   "The customers start coming in at about 11 a.m., and there
is a line" until dark, says Elaine Hobbs, a co-owner of La
Tienda. Lottery business has been so brisk that the store
enlarged its parking lot and opened a special "scratcher
room," where lottery players sit at picnic tables and peel
away the masking on their instant-style tickets in search of
a winner. It also plans to add a lottery service window to
separate buyers of lottery tickets from regular customers,
some of whom have had to suffer hour-long waits just to pay
for snacks or gasoline.
   The inflow of cold cash isn't the first that La Tienda has
enjoyed because of Utah's political realities, which include
restrictive liquor laws. Long before it became a mecca for
Utah lottery players, notes Mrs. Hobbs, it did a brisk
business selling more than 100 varieties of beer -- most of
which aren't available in Utah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   General Dynamics to Pay
   $527,000 in Job-Bias Case
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR GD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- General Dynamics Corp. agreed to pay
$527,000 in back pay and salary increases to minority and
women workers as part of a settlement of government job
discrimination charges.
   The Labor Department's contract-compliance office said the
defense contractor's Space Systems division in San Diego
didn't fully carry out its affirmative-action program. The
office identified several practices it alleged to be
discriminatory.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics agreed to the settlement without
admitting the charges.
   The Space Systems division agreed to extend job
opportunities to black engineering applicants allegedly
screened out of positions, and to give $268,771 in back pay
to 21 black individuals, the compliance office said. The
contractor also reviewed the salaries that it pays to
minorities and women, and raised the pay by $258,590 for 42
minority men and women and 61 non-minority women.
</TEXT>
