<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   RJR Hopes Smell
   Of Success Is Sweet
   With New Cigarette
   ---
   `Horizon,' Vanilla Scented,
   Is Company's Second Shot
   At a Less Stinky Smoke
   ----
   By Peter Waldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   RJR
</CO>
<IN>
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   A little more than a year after introducing Chelsea, "the
first cigarette that smells good," RJR Nabisco has begun
test-marketing Horizon, "the first cigarette that smells
good."
   The food and tobacco giant, still pushing to design a
cigarette that is less annoying to nonsmokers, hasn't
formally introduced Horizon, but "scratch and sniff"
pamphlets trumpeting the brand arrived on doorsteps in
Atlanta last week. The company has been hawking Chelsea in
other test markets since March 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both Chelsea and Horizon exude a scent similar to vanilla
that RJR marketers think is less objectionable to nonsmokers
than typical cigarette smoke. The brands have slightly
different blends of tobacco, said an RJR spokeswoman, but
they use the same paper to give off the unusual scent.
   RJR has found that Chelsea, targeted at women, is equally
popular among men and women. Horizon, the spokeswoman said,
"gives us an opportunity to test one brand vs. another and to
see whether the {sweetsmelling} attribute itself is what
people are looking for, or whether the image of the brand can
change how smokers feel about it."
   But one marketing executive with another large tobacco
company said the introduction of Horizon suggests that RJR
isn't happy with Chelsea. The executive, who asked not to be
identified, said her company's tally puts Chelsea with a 0.2%
share of the cigarette market in its test areas in
Pennsylvania and Nevada, and a 0.5% share in Florida. Those
numbers, she said, are below what companies normally require
before rolling out a product nationwide.
   RJR declined to comment on the numerical results of its
test-marketing.
   RJR may be running into the same problems that it
encountered when it introduced the heralded Premier
"smokeless cigarette" in test markets in 1988. The $300
million experiment flopped in part because RJR, trying to
find a cigarette or a facsimile to satisfy nonsmokers'
concerns, ignored basic needs of smokers, such as the
cigarette's taste, smell and feel.
   Judging from RJR's pamphlet on Horizon, the new cigarette,
too, is primarily aimed at the concerns of nonsmokers. Large
letters on the three-page fold-out tell smokers: "You
shouldn't have to apologize," "You shouldn't have to make
excuses," and "You shouldn't have to leave the room." The
advertisement goes on to say: "You'll also be pleased to know
that Horizon won't leave your clothes, hair, car and home
smelling like your regular cigarettes."
   Jeffery Wack, a professor of public health at Yale
University and a marketing consultant with Marketing Sciences
Inc. in New Haven, Conn., doubts that nonsmokers will take
any more kindly to aromatic cigarettes than normal varieties,
as long as they contain the same carcinogens. "If the
pollutants are still there but it just smells differently,"
he said, "you don't eliminate the major objection."
   But the RJR spokeswoman said: "We think the concept is
sound enough to warrant tinkering with and coming up with an
alternative brand. If we believed it wasn't, we wouldn't do
it."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0110
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0110.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Payment Delays
   Of Soviets Hurt
   Western Firms
   ----
   By Laurie Hays
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST MITSY J.CIT J.MIB J.NIW DD G.HFA
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- A number of small Western businesses that
haven't been paid by Soviet foreign trade organizations for
many months are suffering serious financial hardship and some
have filed claims with their export insurers.
   Diplomats and bankers attempting to negotiate settlements
with the Soviets say the problem of payment delays, which
began last year, doesn't seem to be improving. Large sums
have been paid following delays in some instances, but then
new delays occur in others. Several Soviet trading firms have
also asked to reschedule their payments until as late as
1993, leading to speculation that the problem may drag on and
that the organizations still don't have enough money to meet
all their obligations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's a very patchy situation," says Don Brown, commercial
counselor to the British Embassy. "They seem to be making
payments to some at the expense of others."
   At least two British traders are suffering severe hardship
now, says Mr. Brown. Another European economic counselor who
doesn't want his country identified says one company he
represents is also near collapse. And a group of minor West
German concerns that together are owed several hundred
million West German marks have applied to Hermes, the
government's export insurance administrator, for
compensation. A spokesman for Hermes in Hamburg says requests
for compensation have "jumped dramatically" in recent months
and now amounts to a "three-digit figure, in the millions."
   It was also reported last week that several of Japan's
major trading houses, including C. Itoh &amp; Co., Mitsui &amp; Co.,
Mitsubishi Corp. and Nissho Iwai Co., have taken the first
steps to claim export insurance because their Soviet trading
partners had delayed payments.
   The British firms haven't yet filed any claims, but have
made numerous inquiries about how they would recoup losses,
says a spokesman for the Export Credit Guarantee Department.
The spokesman adds that he hopes that embarassment will drive
the Soviets to pay the bills before an avalanche of claims
comes in. Meanwhile, the department is offering advice on how
payments might be negotiated.
   While initially one main trading organization for
chemicals called Soyuzkhimexport was blamed for late
payments, the delays now seem to have spread to many other
industries, including steel, machinery and technology. The
total amount owed has been estimated at at least $500
million.
   Soviet officials blame the delays on chaos resulting from
a decentralization of the foreign trade system. While Soviet
exports and imports used to be a simple and reliable
transaction handled through several government-run trade
organizations, more than 12,000 enterprises now trade
directly with the West. Many of them aren't balancing their
books properly and have depleted the system of currency, the
officials say.
   "I guess they have no money," says Boris O. Kozhevnikov,
director of the law and treaty department at the USSR Chamber
of Commerce and Industry.
   Large delegations of European government officials have
come to Moscow in recent months to negotiate payments and
avoid depleting their export insurance reserves. Later this
month, West German ministers plan to take up the problem at
the Commission for Economic Cooperation, according to
Wolfgang von Lingelsheim-Seibicke, a counselor at the West
German embassy.
   While bigger companies like the chemical concerns Du Pont
Co. and Hoechst AG have been annoyed by the delays and in
some cases have stopped shipping goods until the payments are
made, they haven't felt the effects as severely as smaller
trading firms that have a majority of their business tied up
with the Soviet Union, the diplomats say. Those smaller firms
must pay their suppliers and the lack of payments from the
Soviet side has hurt them badly.
   The officials have declined to identify the companies,
while the companies themselves, saying they feared angering
their Soviet partners, refuse to comment. By discussing the
situation, the companies would risk losing not only payments,
but future business, the officials say.
   ---
   Timothy Aeppel in Bonn and Tim Carrington in London
contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0109
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0109.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   American Express
   To Accept Deposits
   From Cardholders
   ----
   By Georgette Jasen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4B
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Express Co. wants more of your money.
   The travel and financial-services giant has a new
"Membership Savings" account, which will pay interest on
deposits made with a cardholder's regular monthly bill. The
interest rate is guaranteed to be higher than the average on
bank money market accounts, and deposits up to $100,000 will
be insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Market research showed that cardholders "really want to
begin saving more," said Sarah M. Nolan, president of the
investment and insurance services group of American Express
Travel Related Services. "They want to have savings made as
easy and habit-forming as spending."
   Under the program, which American Express plans to
introduce in eight states and the District of Columbia this
month and nationwide by the end of the year, cardmembers who
sign up will be billed a specified amount to go into the
savings account each month. To withdraw funds, they can call
a toll-free telephone number to receive a check, or, for a
$10 fee, the money can be wired into a cardholder's bank
account.
   American Express will "make prudent investments" with the
funds deposited, Ms. Nolan said, "nothing different than what
any financial institution would do." She declined to be more
specific.
   Separately, American Express is offering certain
cardholders a line of credit at an interest rate of nine
percentage points over the prime rate. With the prime
currently at 10%, the rate on the line of credit would be
19%.
   "We consider ourselves a broad-based financial
institution," said Ms. Nolan, adding that the two new
products are "attempts to satisfy our cardmembers."
   The line of credit is being offered through American
Express Centurion Bank, based in Wilmington, Del. The savings
account is offerd by American Express Resource Co., an
industrial loan corporation chartered in Utah, which Ms.
Nolan said "meets the regulations and requirements" for FDIC
insurance.
   The interest rate on the savings account is pegged at half
a percentage point more than the average of the 100 largest
banks and thrifts in the nation, as published weekly by Bank
Rate Monitor, a North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter. The
average is now 6.06%, which would mean a 6.56% rate on the
American Express account.
   A number of banks and thrifts, however, are offering more
than 7% on money market accounts, and the average yield on
money market mutual funds is currently just below 8%.
Nevertheless, Ms. Nolan said, American Express expects "an
enthusiastic reception" for the new savings account because
of its convenience and the small minimum deposit of $50.
   Participants in the program can deposit more or less than
the specified amount, or miss a deposit. The account is being
introduced in Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Maryland,
Virginia, Georgia, Wisconsin, Ohio, Oregon and in Washington,
D.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
