<LP>
   BUDGET TALKS MAY BEGIN soon between the White House and
Congress. Four top congressional leaders told Bush yesterday
they are ready to begin negotiations on a package of big tax
increases and spending cuts aimed at sharply reducing the
federal deficit. Bush also signaled his willingness to
consider raising taxes, House GOP leader Michel said.
"Everything is on the table," Rep. Michel quoted the
president as saying.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Group of Seven backed a 50% capital increase for the
IMF and appeared to agree on revised rankings for the IMF's
top contributors. The group also said the yen's continued
weakness "may have undesirable consequences" but noted
currency markets have stabilized recently.
   ---
   Corporate profits fell 18% in the first quarter, hurt by
increased labor costs, higher interest payments and unusually
big write-offs, a Journal survey shows. Analysts expect
profits to remain soft in the current quarter but to pick up
in the second half.
   ---
   The jobless rate rose to 5.4% in April from 5.2% the
previous month, indicating continued weakness in the economy.
The increase surprised many analysts because of recent signs
the economy was picking up.
                                                                                                       

   Stock and bond prices rallied Friday as the jobless report
eased speculation that the Fed may tighten credit soon. The
dollar finished mixed.
   ---
   Drexel paid creditors over $600 million in the three
months before it filed for Chapter 11 protection, which means
the payments may be recoverable under federal bankruptcy law,
according to bankruptcy lawyers.
   ---
   First Executive has hired First Boston to explore a
restructuring of the struggling Los Angles-based insurer that
could include the sale of one or more operating units,
sources said.
   ---
   Two Campeau units, Allied Stores and Federated, posted
fiscal 1990 losses totaling $2.43 billion.
   ---
   Insurers won another legal battle against California's
Proposition 103. A Los Angeles judge invalidated a key aspect
of the 1988 auto-insurance law.
   ---
   Columbia S&amp;L posted a $293.3 million loss for the first
quarter, reflecting further decay in its junk-bond holdings.
But officials claimed progress in an effort to sell the
bonds.
                                                                                                       

   Far West Financial reported a $26.2 million quarterly
loss, leaving the Belzberg-controlled California thrift firm
short of a capital requirement.
   ---
   Fox Broadcasting won FCC permission to offer added
programming without having to adhere to network TV rules
affecting rerun sales.
                                                                                                       

   NBC News plans to launch a 24hour news service similar to
CNN's Headline News, sources said.
   ---
   Brazil began opening its market to more imports, including
telephone equipment, as promised. But high import duties were
imposed on most items to protect domestic firms.
   ---
   Saatchi &amp; Saatchi fired two top executives in a power
struggle that was won by the ad giant's new chief executive,
Robert Louis-Dreyfus.
   ---
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh is likely to tap D. Leonard Wise, a
steel industry veteran, as chief executive after the company
emerges from Chapter 11.
   ---
   Several small Western firms are being severely hurt by
continued payment delays by Soviet concerns. Some of the
Western businesses have filed claims with export insurers.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 140,550,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2710.36, up 14.19; transportation 1145.09, up 4.62; utilities
208.38, up 2.27.
