<HL>
   Quarterly Review of Corporate Earnings:
   First Quarter, 1990
   ---
   Companies' Net Income Fell 18%;
   Despite Some Pickup in Economy
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   The U.S. economy is displaying fresh signs of life, but
corporate earnings still are sagging. Many securities
analysts look for another soft profits showing in the current
quarter but expect a pickup in the second half.
   In the 1990 first quarter, net income of 654 major
corporations fell 18% from a year earlier, a Wall Street
Journal survey finds. This compared with a 14% drop in last
year's fourth quarter. After-tax earnings on continuing
operations fell 15%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The inflation-adjusted gross national product rose at an
annual rate of 2.1% in the first quarter -- hardly
spectacular but a substantial improvement over the 1.1% gain
in the fourth quarter. But profits were depressed by
increases in labor costs and interest payments. In addition,
earnings were held down by unusually large writeoffs. In
part, banks were writing off bad loans, but Susan Lakatos, a
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. economist, says that, in addition,
"corporate America is still cleaning up its balance sheet."
   Melissa R. Brown, a Prudential-Bache Securities analyst,
has been pessimistic about earnings for some time, but she
says first-quarter profits "came in worse than expected.
Although earnings for the quarter are not wildly
disappointing, there's not much to cheer about." Even sectors
that did a little better than expected, she says, did less
well than a year ago.
   Richard D. Rippe of Dean Witter Reynolds, however,
believes that continuing moderate increases in growth will
raise business volume. By later this year he expects rising
capacity utilization to widen profit margins. He expects
pretax reported profits for the full year to decline somewhat
less than they did in 1989 and predicts a sharp gain in
earnings in 1991.
   The 51 economists interviewed monthly by Blue Chip
Economic Indicators in general share Mr. Rippe's view. Last
month on the average they forecast a 2.4% drop in pretax
profits this year, down from the 8.3% drop in 1989. But they
predicted that earnings would rise by 7.4% in 1991.
   Among major groups, profits were down sharply in autos,
oil and steel. Most aerospace concerns posted gains but some
had major downturns. Computer company results were mixed.
   The Big Three auto makers took strong medicine to cut
bulging North American vehicle inventories and suffered the
side effects of sharply lower profits. General Motors, Ford
and Chrysler shut nearly all of their U.S. factories for one
to two weeks during January, and slowed output during the
rest of the January-to-March period. At the same time, the
Big Three continued to offer heavy discounts in an effort to
stimulate a sluggish market and hold ground against Japanese
competitors.
   Detroit's first-quarter retrenchment rippled back to auto
parts makers, who saw sales volumes and profits squeezed hard
during the period. And it didn't help relations with the
United Auto Workers union, which will negotiate new contracts
with the Big Three this fall. On the positive side, overall
Big Three inventories now are at relatively lean levels.
   One-time gains last year at Boeing, McDonnell Douglas and
GenCorp create the deceptive appearance of a sharp drop in
first-quarter aerospace and defense industry profitability.
But quarterly earnings for most companies actually rose this
year, and Boeing's operating profit -- after negating a $298
million credit in 1989 from an accounting change -- surged
87% on the strength of its booming airliner deliveries.
Northrop's rise in net income included $67 million in the
latest quarter from the sale of its headquarters building.
Lockheed got better results from its technological services
and aeronautical systems segments -- and found itself free of
write-downs for a change. Wolfgang Demisch of UBS Securities
noted that despite having operating earnings that generally
have been "really quite upbeat," defense companies, with few
exceptions, have had their stocks hammered because of the
turmoil in the Pentagon budget. Wall Street's reaction, he
says, reflects that even if short-term earnings are strong,
"it's hard to make out a scenario where the aerospace results
will accelerate from here on out."
   Computer makers showed wide variations in profits. But
industry watchers were generally heartened by
better-than-expected news from the two biggest players,
International Business Machines and Digital Equipment, and
they talked of a possible revival in domestic demand, which
has been sluggish for years.
   IBM's strong showing, which included the company's best
U.S. results in recent memory, surprised Wall Street and sent
the stock surging. But IBM has had isolated good quarters
before, and analysts cautioned that the company soon may face
competitive pressures in its backbone business of mainframe
computers.
   Even though Digital's profit fell 90% on a $150 million
charge, analysts were relieved that the company didn't post a
loss, as had been feared. In addition, Digital posted its
first rise in domestic sales in four quarters. Because NCR
and Tandem Computers also had reported modest gains in U.S.
business, analysts smelled a trend and said reports of the
home market's death might have been exaggerated.
   Crude oil prices that were $3 to $4 a barrel higher
boosted exploration and production profits of the major oil
companies. Higher natural gas prices early in the quarter
also contributed. But petrochemical profits declined, largely
because crude is the main feedstock for chemicals. Gasoline
refining and marketing profits were generally weaker for the
same reason. Texaco a year earlier took a $1.19 billion gain
from the sale of Texaco Canada Inc., throwing off results for
the company and the group. Phillips had gains totaling $238
million in the latest quarter and a $90 million charge. Exxon
had a $535 million gain a year earlier.
   Steel industry profits were reduced by sharply lower
volumes and weaker prices because of the general slump in
manufacturing. Auto plant shutdowns and efforts by other
major steel users to cut inventories whacked steel operations
to less than 80% of capacity during January, and the mills
didn't get up to 85% of capacity until the last half of
March. By contrast, the industry operated at nearly 90% of
capacity during the 1989 first quarter. Bethlehem Steel had a
$55 million restructuring charge in the 1989 quarter.
   While the outlook is brighter for the second quarter,
profits, nonetheless, will fall well below the year-ago
period, when most manufacturing was booming. "It remains to
be seen whether the second quarter will be just the
seasonally strongest quarter in a weak year, or something
better than that," says Jeffrey F. Miller, metals analyst
with Duff &amp; Phelps. Shipments of many types of steel are
relatively good, reflecting a general improvement in U.S.
manufacturing and an end to six months or more of inventory
reduction.
   Here are the first-quarter profits for various industry
groups and comparisons with the year-earlier quarter. When
individual companies report for three-month periods other
than calendar quarters, the nearest comparable periods are
used. In all the tables, 000s are omitted.
                                                                                                       

   BASIC MATERIALS
                                                                                                       

    1ST QTR. 1990           1ST QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

      4,065,287               5,313,582           - 23
                                                                                                       

   Aluminum companies felt the manufacturing slowdown in the
quarter. Profits dropped sharply, mainly because of lower
prices. Aluminum ingot prices dropped 40% from a year
earlier; prices for sheet and most other products also
declined, but by a lesser amount. In addition, Aluminum Co.
of America lost can sheet sales because it refused to match
an industry price cut last fall. Aluminum's outlook is
brightening as the manufacturing economy picks up. Shipments
are increasing, and the price of ingot has started to rise.
Nonetheless, second-quarter profits are expected to fall well
below the year-ago period, the peak earnings quarter in an
extremely strong year.
   Some gold companies boosted output significantly and sold
their gold for higher prices, mitigating the impact of higher
cash mining costs. Homestake, for example, increased gold
production by about 33% and sold its gold for about $14 an
ounce more than the year before, posting a nearly twofold
increase in earnings.
   Copper companies' earnings declined on a 20% to 30% drop
in realized copper prices.
   Forest products concerns saw profits drop, citing
softening pulp and paper markets. Georgia-Pacific was also
hurt by higher interest expenses. Besides a decline in price
and demand for pulp, Louisiana-Pacific blamed unusually wet
weather that slowed building activity and precluded some
logging, and uncertainty over interest rates. Willamette was
helped by increased operating efficiencies and
stronger-than-expected building materials markets. At
Weyerhaeuser, lower prices and margins in most pulp and paper
markets were only partially offset by improved results in
forest products.
   Paper companies saw profits fall, citing price
discounting. Bowater's profit drop reflected increased
discounting in the newsprint, coated-paper and pulp markets.
Union Camp cited lower prices for linerboard and uncoated
business paper. Boise Cascade was hurt by lower prices and
sluggish demand for most of its paper grades.
   Chemical industry earnings were down because of weak
demand, price declines and cold weather-related increases in
raw materials costs. Many companies, including Dow, Du Pont
and Monsanto, were affected by slowdowns in the U.S. auto and
construction industries. Analysts say most companies will
continue with flat to negative earnings comparisons this
quarter.
                                                                                                       

