   ENERGY
                                                                                                       

    1ST QTR. 1990           1ST QTR. 1989       % CHG.
                                                                                                       

      4,540,201               6,251,198          - 27
                                                                                                       

   A pickup in oil field activity in the U.S. and continued
exploration activity world-wide contributed to strong gains
for the equipment companies and drillers. While the increase
in activity was not huge, companies have trimmed so much from
their cost structures that any increase in business flows
quickly to the bottom line. Even some long-suffering contract
drilling companies, which narrowed their losses, believe an
end to their red ink is in sight.
   Natural gas pipeline companies, despite one of the warmest
first quarters on record, managed generally higher net in
come, what with special items, non-pipeline operations and
Panhandle's acquisition of Texas Eastern. Panhandle's results
for the rest of 1990 will be hurt by high interest expense,
possible cash refunds to customers and ambitious capital
spending.
   Coal industry results were mixed, with good weather,
productivity gains and mining expansions helping some
producers boost profits. Ashland Coal revenue grew 18%,
largely from the recent acquisition of new mines.
                                                                                                       

