   ---
   INDUSTRIAL
                                                                                                       

    1ST QTR. 1990           1ST QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

      2,730,744               3,646,449           - 25
                                                                                                       

   The rail group's earnings decline reflected a drop in
carloadings of motor vehicles, metal products and other
higher-value freight. But Burlington Northern and Norfolk
Southern benefited from strong coal shipments. First-quarter
losses at Santa Fe resulted from a litigation settlement.
Some analysts predict modest rail-traffic gains in the second
quarter.
   Trucking company profits were hurt by higher fuel and
labor costs as continued rate discounting held down revenue.
Consolidated Freightways' first-quarter results reflected
losses at its Emery Worldwide air-freight unit.
   The two largest air-freight carriers, Federal Express and
United Parcel Service, are still racking up large operating
losses on their efforts to expand overseas, offset somewhat
by recent price stabilization in the U.S. Federal Express is
also still struggling to meld its Tiger purchase,
particularly the seniority lists of its pilots. Paul
Schlesinger, an analyst with Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
expects revenue for the industry to continue growing in the
10%-to-15%-a-year range, with profit growth remaining spotty.
   Among the marine transport concerns, American President's
loss stemmed from competitive pressures in its Asia
transportation business and thinner profit margins at its
freight-brokerage operation.
   The sharp slump in the market for big trucks, diesel
engines and other parts continued to depress profits.
Cummins, which supplies about half the diesel engines for
heavy-duty trucks, said first-quarter production in North
America for those trucks fell 23% from a year ago. Although
they expect no immediate rebound, some companies, including
Cummins and Eaton, predict improved truck demand late in
1990.
   Several heavy-machinery makers continued to benefit from
increased demand for their products, though some reported
slowdowns in certain areas. Clark Equipment, for example,
said its U.S. forklift and off-highway components businesses
are in a "slight downturn." Although business for equipment
used in road repairs and mining remains strong, Caterpillar
continues to be hurt by soft demand for machines used in
private construction projects, particularly in the U.S. It's
not optimistic about the rest of the year. But Deere is
likely to continue its strong gains in agricultural machinery
as farmers continue their mini-spending spree. Larry D.
Hollis, an analyst at Robert W. Baird &amp; Co. in Milwaukee,
said improved industrial production later in the year should
help machinery makers.
                                                                                                       

