   TECHNOLOGY
                                                                                                       

    1ST QTR. 1990           1ST QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

      4,316,331               5,061,374           - 15
                                                                                                       

   In office equipment, results were down, but one-time items
masked some bright spots. Xerox reported record losses on a
$375 million charge related to bad real estate investments,
but it posted strong profit gains in its core
document-processing operation. Analysts noted, however, that
revenue on equipment sales rose a meager 2%, and they feared
for the rest of the year.
   Is the chip industry out of the woods after a year of
sluggish growth? Semiconductor sales are up, chip gluts have
dried up, prices have stopped plummeting and makers have even
put some semiconductors on allocation, sparking a barrage of
better-than-expected profit reports. But chip makers warn
that it's too soon to know whether the pickup will last.
Although National Semicondcutor posted a loss, it reported
strong bookings late in the period.
   Software and data processing companies reported mixed
results. Ashton-Tate's performance was hurt because of
continuing delays in shipping new data-base products, while
Oracle Systems reported only a slight earnings increase
because of an unexpected accounting glitch that resulted in
lower-than-expected revenue. Microsoft showed strong gains as
did Lotus, whose performance benefited by comparison with a
relatively weak year-ago quarter.
   Profits from telecommunications services defied a
generally weak earnings environment as traffic volume from
corporate customers remained brisk and cost-reduction
programs improved margins. The second quarter and beyond
could bring further profit boosts as carriers begin to sell
services based on features rather than price. Market leader
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph couldn't match its profit
growth of 18% in last year's first quarter.
   On the equipment side, cut-throat pricing and sluggish
orders from phone companies and corporate customers continued
to hurt margins. This probably won't improve much through the
next quarter.
                                                                                                       

