   FINANCIAL SERVICES

    1ST QTR. 1990           1ST QTR. 1989        % CHG.
                                                                                                       

      5,869,510               7,321,615           - 20
                                                                                                       

   For banks, "the first quarter was an extremely difficult
period," said James J. McDermott Jr. of Keefe, Bruyette &amp;
Woods Inc. Looking at the 150 banking companies Keefe tracks,
results showed a 1% median earnings decline. Results varied
widely by region: Banks in the Northeast showed a 30% decline
-- reflecting "a lot of real estate problems" -- while banks
in the West were up 11%, the analyst said. Banks continued to
be hounded by bad loans and lower corporate-finance fees, but
some bucked the trend. The top two, Citicorp and Chase,
boosted provisions for possible losses on real estate loans;
Citicorp's consumer business world-wide continued strong,
however. Absent an accounting change in the latest period,
J.P. Morgan's net fell 6%. And looking ahead, "pressures
evident in the first quarter are likely to be visited" on the
industry in the second period, as the "economy continues soft
and credit quality remains an ongoing concern," he said.
   The increases in premium rates that many property/casualty
insurers had expected to see failed to materialize.
Underwriting results deteriorated because of the weak
pricing. Companies writing personal auto and other consumer
insurance products, such as Aetna Life &amp; Casualty, Cigna,
Travelers, Xerox's Crum &amp; Forster unit, and New Hampshire
Insurance, a unit of American International Group, have
announced plans to cut back on their personal lines or leave
this business entirely as a way to stem losses.
   Several thrifts benefited from increased interest income
and improved margins, in part because of measures implemented
under last summer's massive thrift bailout.
   Though the bailout has largely flopped, it did enable
regulators to shut down some of the sicker thrifts, which had
been paying large premiums to attract deposits; those
premiums had forced up funding costs, even at healthy
thrifts. As some of the sick thrifts have been closed,
funding costs at many institutions have come down, boosting
margins. Great Western Financial's net interest margin -- the
difference between what it pays for money and earns on assets
-- rose to 3.01 from 2.43 a year ago, helping lift net
interest income 24% to a record $286 million. H.F. Ahmanson's
net interest margin increased to 2.68 from 2.41 and net
interest income rose 21% to $286.4 million; it also generated
$3.1 billion from loan sales, compared with $249 million from
loan sales a year earlier. Golden West, which has the
toughest cost controls in the industry, saw net interest
income increase 24% to $125.2 million.
   Securities brokers' profits remained depressed in a
sluggish investment-banking environment and a falling stock
market. But year-to-year profit comparisons were generally
positive because the year-earlier period was also a poor one.
Most big brokerage firms, including industry leader Merrill
Lynch, suffered 20% to 30% declines in investment banking
revenue. Salomon's profit turnaround resulted from trading
gains for its own account, which offset losses in its
commodities unit. The bright spot for brokers was that most
continued to increase customer assets under management.
Analysts say brokers' earnings will remain weak this quarter.
                                                                                                       

