<HL>
   Technology:
   Pfizer Can Be Sued for Alleged Anxiety
   Caused by Heart Valve, Court Rules
   ----
   By Michael Waldholz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   PFE
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL SUPPLIES (MDS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Pfizer Inc. can be sued by a woman who claims that concern
about the quality of her implanted heart valve made by a
Pfizer unit has caused her anxiety, California's Supreme
Court ruled.
   Under the ruling, Judy Kahn, a Virginia woman, can sue
Pfizer's Shiley Inc. unit for damages even though her heart
valve is working properly. In January, a California appeals
court ruled that Mrs. Kahn could sue Shiley, which is based
in Irvine, Calif., but Pfizer had appealed that decision to
the state's Supreme Court.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   News of the higher court's decision late Thursday spread
quickly through Wall Street and among heart valve recipients.
Pfizer has succeeded in having 19 other similar cases
dismissed by the courts. Mrs. Kahn, therefore, is expected to
be the first of perhaps several hundred recipients who could
sue Shiley in California for anxiety-related damages.
   In New York, Pfizer said it will defend itself
"vigorously." The company said it believed Mrs. Kahn and
other similar cases face "stringent legal and factual
burdens."
   Still, the court's decision sent Pfizer shares shuddering,
falling more than $2 in New York Stock Exchange trading
during the day Friday, and closing at $57, down 87.5 cents.
Pfizer was also the most-actively traded Big Board stock on
Friday. The company's shares have dropped from about $70 in
January when concern about the company's liability received
publicity.
   Analysts said the ruling meant there would be a cloud of
uncertainty hanging over Pfizer until the case goes to jury.
"It means the {heart valve problems} are going to be around
for a while," said James Keeney of Mabon, Nugent &amp; Co. Mr.
Keeney said the valve problem may be the "catalyst" to force
the company to shed some slow-growing businesses or buy back
shares.
   In Minneapolis, Mrs. Kahn's lawyer said he didn't expect
the case to go to trial in Orange County Superior Court in
California until late 1991 because of the immense amount of
documents that needed to be addressed. The attorney, Bruce
Finzen of Robins, Kaplan, Miller &amp; Ciresi, said there are
about one million pages of documents to work through. Mr.
Finzen said there are 200 similar cases that he could bring
to suit after this one.
   The Kahn case stems from structural problems associated
with the Shiley-Bjork convexo-concave valve. The valve was
pulled from use in the mid-1980s when it was found that a
defect caused the valve to fracture. Pfizer said that by the
beginning of this year, 389 valves had broken and 248
patients had died, while about 56,000 people were alive with
working valves.
   The company said it has settled numerous suits related to
the failed valves, but it has refused to settle claims made
by those people whose valves are still working. It said it
has sufficient reserves to cover the cases it expects to
settle.
   Pfizer said that Mrs. Kahn's lawyers must prove in court
that Pfizer and Shiley engaged in "deceit" in marketing and
testing the valves. The New York-based health-care company
said proving deceit is "difficult." The company also noted
that a federal court in Missouri recently rejected claims
similar to those made by Mrs. Kahn's lawyers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Campeau Units
   Post a Deficit
   Of $2.43 Billion
   ---
   Federated and Allied Stores
   Attribute Much of Loss
   To Non-Cash Charges
   ----
   By Robert Melnbardis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   CMAFC
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
EARNINGS (ERN)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. and Allied Stores Corp.
had after-tax losses totaling $2.43 billion in fiscal 1990
after big non-cash charges that include a $1.15 billion
write-down of good will in Federated in the fourth quarter.
   In their Form 10-K filings with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the Campeau Corp. units attributed the
bulk of their losses to non-cash accounting treatments of
their Chapter 11 bankrupcty status.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Federated's $1.5 billion net loss for the 53 weeks ended
Feb. 3 includes a $1.15 billion write-down of good will,
reflecting the company's "deteriorating financial situation"
during the year. It said further adjustments may be made to
good will during its efforts to restructure and emerge from
Chapter 11 proceedings.
   Allied's share of Federated's write-down and equity in
losses at Campeau's Ralphs Grocery Co. chain totaled $660.3
million, bringing its net loss to $925.2 million for the
year. Allied owns 50% of Federated and has direct and
indirect equity stakes in Ralphs, a Southern California
supermarket chain.
   In a summary of their 10-K filings, the department store
operators said that despite "extreme pressures" on their
operations in the third and fourth quarters,
comparable-division sales were up by 7.2% to $4.87 billion at
Federated and increased by 5.2% to $2.71 billion at Allied.
They said combined net interest expenses of $806.7 million
took one of the "biggest bites" out of their annual earnings.
The retailers said the write-down of good will and interest
charges had "little or no bearing" on their operations since
they sought Chapter 11 bankrupcty protection on Jan. 15.
   Under Chapter 11, a company continues to operate under
court protection from its creditors while it tries to work
out a plan to pay its bills.
   In other financial information provided to the U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in Cincinnati, Federated and Allied said
operations continue to improve since January, when many
vendors resumed shipping merchandise to their department
stores. Their net losses for the five weeks ended April 7
totaled $18 million, compared with $48 million for the four
weeks ended March 3. Sales at Federated and Allied in the
latest five weeks were $405.3 million and $234.4 million,
respectively.
   In a statement, Allen Questrom, chairman and chief
executive of the retailers, said they have "turned the corner
on stabilizing the business."
   "The results do very little other than confirm something
which we already know, namely that Federated and Allied are
sound and reasonably good retailing operations," said Kurt
Barnard, publisher of Retail Marketing Report, a New
York-based industry newsletter.
   But the figures also show, he said, that despite their
improving retail health since January, Federated and Allied
can't escape from the "intolerable ocean of debt" Campeau
plunged them into. "That's why we all shuddered when we saw
what Campeau was doing to those stores," Mr. Barnard said.
   In its 10-K filing, Federated blamed its financial woes on
the massive debt it was burdened with by Campeau's $6.6
billion highly leveraged buy-out of Federated in May 1988.
"Ultimately, this drain on revenues from the company's
{Federated's} retail operation contributed to cash shortfalls
which precipitated the company's Chapter 11 filing," it said.
   Federated said most of its cash interest outlays are
frozen by its Chapter 11 status and it is no longer accruing
annual interest charges of about $200 million on its
unsecured debt. Its interest expense is expected to drop by
between $375 million and $400 million, it said. In fiscal
1990 Federated had interest expense of $516.1 million, it
said. Allied is no longer accruing annual interest of about
$90 million on its unsecured debt. It had net interest
expense of $290.6 million in fiscal 1990.
   Federated said it also wrote off $120.5 million of
unamortized deferred financing costs and reorganization
expenses incurred after its acquisition by Campeau. Allied
had $21.6 million in reorganization costs and $138.8 million
in income tax expense.
   The units said they had combined cash on hand of $552
million on April 25, and hadn't drawn on a total of $700
million in debtor-in-possession financing available for
working capital needs.
   Separately, in an information circular for a special
meeting of holders of its 7 1/2% convertible debentures,
Campeau said it plans to sell a "substantial portion" of its
real estate assets to restructure its own ailing finances.
The circular said Campeau has a "significant negative cash
flow" as a result of its debt-service obligations, and the
assets sales would leave it with a positive cash flow.
   The sales are expected to generate enough cash to repay
secured debt on the properties, it said. Secured loans on
other properties would be serviced using cash flow from the
properties, and senior unsecured creditors would begin
receiving payments after "substantial completion" of the
planned asset sales "only to the extent that cash is
available following certain deductions." Campeau also
proposes the accrual of dividends on preferred shares, with
no retractions or redemptions.
   Campeau said its investment in and advances to its U.S.
units totaled $1.27 billion as of Jan. 31, and it plans to
participate in their restructuring.
   Campeau has 184 million Canadian dollars (US$157.7
million) of 7 1/2% debentures outstanding. At the June 1
meeting, debenture holders will be asked to approve a
resolution to waive existing and future defaults and to defer
interest payable on the debentures until Dec. 31, 1991.
Support for the resolution by holders of two-thirds of the
debentures is almost assured because Campeau Chairman Robert
Campeau and his wife are able to vote 42% of the debentures,
and the Reichmann family's Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd.
holds another 25.3%.
   Campeau defaulted on the debentures in March when it
missed interest payments on that series and $260 million of
convertible debentures held by Olympia &amp; York. Sources close
to the Reichmanns have said previously that Olympia &amp; York
would support the interest deferrals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0009
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0009.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   NBC Reportedly Plans News Service
   Operating 24 Hours for Its Affiliates
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GE TBSA
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- NBC News is planning to launch a 24-hour news
service, similar to Cable News Network's Headline News, and
offer it to the network's 208 affiliates, according to people
familiar with the proposal.
   Although plans aren't finalized, NBC News, a division of
National Broadcasting Co., reportedly would provide fully
produced newscasts -- with anchors separate from NBC News --
to affiliates during periods when the network isn't
operating. For example, NBC doesn't transmit programming for
several hours during the morning beginning at 9 a.m., in the
afternoon beginning at 4 p.m. and overnight beginning at 2
a.m.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Also, the network is "dark" during many hours on the
weekend, when affiliates must provide their own programming
or buy it from syndicators.
   NBC is planning to announce details of the service in June
at its annual convention with affiliates in Washington. It
would be offered exclusively to NBC affiliates.
   It would be the first time a broadcast network attempted
to distribute news and informational programming on an
around-the-clock basis.
   "Affiliates could take this news and informational
programming during some of those (dark) periods," said an NBC
official, who didn't want to be identified. "This is an
alternative to NBC stations that don't necessarily want to
buy syndicated shows but want to enhance their news image."
   NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., declined to comment.
However, the NBC official said discussions have taken place
over the past several months and have focused on the
service's content, its value to affiliates and how it will be
distributed. Although there has been discussion that the
service will be based in Dallas, no final decision has been
made.
   There is a possibility that NBC News, the only network
news division that didn't make a profit last year, would
eventually sell the service overseas. CNN, for example, sells
its programming world-wide. However, the NBC official said no
discussions for overseas distribution have been held.
   The network already has a service, called A-News, that
delivers footage and news reports from NBC News and NBC
affiliates. The stations pick which stories they want to air
on local newscasts. It is unclear how the new 24-hour service
would affect A-News. It also isn't clear if NBC Cable's
network, Consumer News and Business Channel, would be
providing material to the service.
   There is additional competition other than Headline News,
however, including the All News Channel, a co-venture between
Conus Communications, a subsidiary of Hubbard Broadcasting
Inc., and Viacom International Inc. An NBC-owned station,
KCNC in Denver, last week agreed to become a subscriber to
the All News Channel.
   About one-fourth of NBC's affiliates already subscribe to
CNN's Headline News, a subsidiary of Turner Broadcasting
System Inc.; Headline News is a separate service of CNN that
is similar to all-news radio, with news, weather and sports
updated every half hour. In fact, Turner and NBC News had
negotiated to form a joint news-gathering operation. When
those talks collapsed in February, NBC News President Michael
Gartner said "a joint operation would not best serve our
affiliates or our viewers." Instead, he said, NBC would
develop a "stronger" news service for the stations.
   NBC News was sharply criticized by its affiliates for its
lackluster performance in getting footage on the air from
last October's San Francisco area earthquake, for instance.
   "I have encouraged NBC to do anything that can make our
news product more valuable," said William L. Bolster, head of
the affiliate board's news committee and general manager of
KSDK, the NBC affiliate in St. Louis.
   NBC News needs to give the stations some good news by June
3, the first day of the network's convention. The affiliates
are furious over the plunging ratings of the formerly No. 1
rated "Today" morning news show, which since January has
slipped to second place behind ABC's "Good Morning America."
Last week's ratings for "Today," for instance, were the
lowest since August 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900507-0008
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900507-0008.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Sotheby's Holdings Inc.:
   Profit Rose 15%, Sales 26%
   During the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   BID
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Sotheby's Holdings Inc. reported that first-quarter net
income rose 15% on strong buying in all collecting areas.
   The New York auction concern's net rose to $6 million, or
10 cents a share, from $5.2 million, or nine cents a share, a
year earlier. Sales grew 26% to $61.4 million from $48.9
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Michael L. Ainslie, Sotheby's president, said that in the
first quarter, auction sales of $282.3 million were up 39%
from a year earlier, with strong buying in Old Master
paintings, jewelry, furniture and rare books.
   Sotheby's shares rose 50 cents Friday to close at $19.75 a
share in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
